131
00:07:52,930 --> 00:07:57,185
<i>Bo Outlaw back quickly.
Kerr tees up a three! Ring it up!</i>

132
00:07:57,852 --> 00:08:00,688
<i>Thirty-seven for Jordan.
I think that's the dagger.</i>

133
00:08:00,771 --> 00:08:03,357
<i>And this one is history.</i>

134
00:08:04,442 --> 00:08:09,113
<i>Chicago Bulls, with an 87-78 victory
over the Orlando Magic,</i>

135
00:08:09,197 --> 00:08:11,782
<i>win their 60th game of the season.</i>

136
00:08:26,547 --> 00:08:27,548
Sixty wins.

137
00:08:34,138 --> 00:08:35,515
After a hard day,

138
00:08:37,099 --> 00:08:38,935
I would take grape Gatorade, but...

139
00:08:40,811 --> 00:08:41,811
I don't think so.

140
00:08:41,854 --> 00:08:44,273
That's all we be thinking about
in the fourth quarter.

141
00:08:44,357 --> 00:08:46,234
- Icy, icy beer.
- Cold beer.

142
00:08:48,653 --> 00:08:49,946
I don't know why y'all filming.

143
00:08:50,029 --> 00:08:52,281
We don't want y'all filming us
drinking no beer.

144
00:08:53,074 --> 00:08:55,034
I don't care what you film.

145
00:08:56,327 --> 00:09:00,915
Hey, if they go back...
go back ten years ago,

146
00:09:00,998 --> 00:09:03,251
you'd see half the brothers
drinking a case.

147
00:09:03,834 --> 00:09:05,211
At halftime!

148
00:09:05,294 --> 00:09:06,754
When I first joined the team,

149
00:09:06,837 --> 00:09:09,298
they was drinking beers
at half and smoking cigarettes.

150
00:09:09,382 --> 00:09:10,591
And you know what?

151
00:09:11,384 --> 00:09:14,637
Shit, they was getting the cigarettes
from the coaches.

152
00:09:17,682 --> 00:09:19,308
Yo, Stan, can I borrow a cigarette?

153
00:09:19,392 --> 00:09:20,392
Motherfucker...

154
00:09:20,434 --> 00:09:22,994
- Your drinking problem...
- Don't tell 'em that.

155
00:09:23,062 --> 00:09:25,207
- I gotta do the press.
- Have to do it?

156
00:09:25,231 --> 00:09:26,941
- I'm going out the other way.
- All right.

157
00:09:28,568 --> 00:09:29,568
How you doing?

158
00:09:29,944 --> 00:09:31,279
Man, you tripping?

159
00:09:32,822 --> 00:09:34,742
So you coming back
next year, Michael?

160
00:09:51,632 --> 00:09:56,137
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,
your world champion Chicago Bulls!</i>

161
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:58,848
Once again, I wanna say thanks.

162
00:09:58,931 --> 00:10:01,350
It's been eight years,
going into my ninth year.

163
00:10:01,434 --> 00:10:05,187
We got two championships,
and hopefully we got a lot left.

164
00:10:05,271 --> 00:10:08,274
Hopefully we can bring more
championships to Chicago. Thanks!

165
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:19,994
<i>You don't have to be a sports
fan to know that this man is beyond human.</i>

166
00:10:20,661 --> 00:10:25,082
<i>At age 30, Jordan has led
the Chicago Bulls to NBA championships,</i>

167
00:10:25,166 --> 00:10:29,003
<i>the Dream Team to an Olympic gold medal,
and most importantly,</i>

168
00:10:29,086 --> 00:10:32,757
<i>he's given America, and the world,
a sorely needed hero.</i>

169
00:10:33,132 --> 00:10:35,509
<i>A Jordan sighting sparks a frenzy.</i>

170
00:10:35,593 --> 00:10:37,762
<i>- His touch, a burst of tears.</i>
- You're good.

171
00:10:37,845 --> 00:10:41,641
<i>And being Mike means being
the most popular human on the planet.</i>

172
00:10:42,183 --> 00:10:45,061
Michael Jordan had become such a huge

173
00:10:45,144 --> 00:10:48,439
cultural figure in the early '90s.

174
00:10:48,981 --> 00:10:51,317
He was so widely celebrated,

175
00:10:52,568 --> 00:10:54,904
inevitably there's going to be someone

176
00:10:54,987 --> 00:10:57,740
who's going to
start trying to find some dirt.

177
00:10:59,367 --> 00:11:01,994
I guess one of the things
that started problems

178
00:11:02,620 --> 00:11:04,914
was Sam Smith's book, <i>Jordan Rules.</i>

179
00:11:06,749 --> 00:11:10,544
I'd been an investigative reporter
when I started my journalism career.

180
00:11:10,628 --> 00:11:12,922
I wasn't a typical sports reporter
coming in.

181
00:11:13,005 --> 00:11:15,800
I was interested in what happened
behind the scenes.

182
00:11:15,883 --> 00:11:19,553
Every time I look up, you've been on TV.
You must be carrying one with you now.

183
00:11:19,637 --> 00:11:22,264
<i>'Cause everybody always said,
"Pull the curtain back.</i>

184
00:11:22,848 --> 00:11:24,767
<i>What really goes on in the locker room?"</i>

185
00:11:25,393 --> 00:11:28,313
When you do books like that,
you gotta have controversial things,

186
00:11:28,354 --> 00:11:33,693
you gotta have things that are, you know,
people would not suspect or know.

187
00:11:33,776 --> 00:11:37,446
<i>The</i> Sun-Times <i>reports the book
details conflicts within the team.</i>

188
00:11:38,531 --> 00:11:40,741
The book outlines
alleged turmoil on the club

189
00:11:40,825 --> 00:11:42,702
during its run for the title last season.

190
00:11:42,785 --> 00:11:46,205
It alleges Jordan was kind of
a tough guy with some of his teammates.

191
00:11:46,288 --> 00:11:48,749
Everybody got tired of seeing
the McDonald's and the Cokes

192
00:11:48,833 --> 00:11:49,875
and all the other stuff.

193
00:11:49,959 --> 00:11:54,255
They really wanted to see something
other than something positive.

194
00:11:54,880 --> 00:11:57,967
I was shocked when it exploded
like it did.

195
00:11:59,176 --> 00:12:04,098
But the book is popular because it made it
public that Michael Jordan is not perfect.

196
00:12:04,181 --> 00:12:05,391
Not everybody loves him.

197
00:12:05,474 --> 00:12:07,601
He wasn't particularly beloved
by his teammates.

198
00:12:08,185 --> 00:12:10,020
<i>Michael told teammates</i>

199
00:12:10,104 --> 00:12:12,982
<i>not to pass the ball to a certain player
during crunch time.</i>

200
00:12:13,065 --> 00:12:15,276
<i>Threatening the others,
saying, if they did it,</i>

201
00:12:15,359 --> 00:12:17,820
<i>they would never
get the ball from him again.</i>

202
00:12:17,903 --> 00:12:21,782
<i>Jordan also allegedly punched
Will Perdue during a practice session.</i>

203
00:12:22,283 --> 00:12:24,660
Everybody loved Michael around the world.

204
00:12:25,745 --> 00:12:27,955
But after Sam Smith's book, <i>Jordan Rules,</i>

205
00:12:28,497 --> 00:12:32,668
there was a certain backlash
and some of the brightness had come off.

206
00:12:35,254 --> 00:12:38,382
People saw a side
that we didn't see before.

207
00:12:39,008 --> 00:12:42,136
<i>Concerning team GM Jerry Krause,
Jordan says,</i>

208
00:12:42,219 --> 00:12:45,848
<i>"This thing isn't over.
I'm going to get that guy fired."</i>

209
00:12:45,931 --> 00:12:47,975
Jerry invited me
to come to his room,

210
00:12:48,058 --> 00:12:53,397
and he had earmarked
about 25 different quotations in the book.

211
00:12:53,981 --> 00:12:56,734
He wanted me to sit and listen to them
while he read them.

212
00:12:57,735 --> 00:13:02,364
And that started with, "Who do you think
could do this? Were you part of this?"

213
00:13:03,073 --> 00:13:05,743
<i>While the early reports have brought
a flurry of denials,</i>

214
00:13:05,826 --> 00:13:08,245
<i>players giving out sensitive information
to the press</i>

215
00:13:08,329 --> 00:13:11,624
<i>is one surefire way
to cause a division within the team.</i>

216
00:13:11,707 --> 00:13:14,335
I didn't contribute to that.
That was Horace.

217
00:13:15,544 --> 00:13:18,631
He was telling everything
that was happening within the group.

218
00:13:20,257 --> 00:13:22,843
As we started
winning championships,

219
00:13:23,594 --> 00:13:27,056
and everybody talked about Michael,
and talked about "everybody else,"

220
00:13:27,807 --> 00:13:31,435
I mean, that really pissed off Horace.

221
00:13:33,020 --> 00:13:36,357
He felt slighted.
He was in Michael's shadow.

222
00:13:37,858 --> 00:13:42,238
No. Not one thing have I ever
divulged to Sam Smith

223
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:46,659
about my relationship
with my former teammates.

224
00:13:47,451 --> 00:13:50,871
A lot of people, because Sam and I
have a great relationship,

225
00:13:50,955 --> 00:13:55,334
used me as a scapegoat, and... so be it.

226
00:13:55,417 --> 00:13:57,169
It couldn't have just been Horace.

227
00:13:57,253 --> 00:13:59,505
Had to be coming from
a number of different places.

228
00:13:59,588 --> 00:14:02,132
It could've been the coaches,

229
00:14:02,216 --> 00:14:05,469
it could've been the owners,
it could've been management.

230
00:14:06,387 --> 00:14:08,556
We have a star
for five or six years,

231
00:14:08,639 --> 00:14:11,141
and then, pretty soon,
people start chipping away

232
00:14:11,225 --> 00:14:13,477
at the pedestal of that star or that hero

