00:14:13,561 --> 00:14:14,979
and try to knock him off the block.

234
00:14:15,813 --> 00:14:18,858
If I'm going to be knocked off
this pedestal,

235
00:14:18,941 --> 00:14:21,610
I'm going to make sure I do something
to be knocked off.

236
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:24,905
I'm not going to let someone else
knock me off for no apparent reason

237
00:14:24,989 --> 00:14:26,824
or comments that I didn't say.

238
00:14:27,992 --> 00:14:29,792
<i>While some of
Michael Jordan's teammates</i>

239
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:31,745
<i>view the book as "a bunch of bull,"</i>

240
00:14:32,329 --> 00:14:36,709
<i>Smith says it may have a positive effect
down the road on the world champions.</i>

241
00:14:37,376 --> 00:14:39,378
I think Phil will use this book
to say,

242
00:14:39,461 --> 00:14:43,632
"Here, this is out there.
They're trying to divide us apart."

243
00:14:43,716 --> 00:14:45,801
In a lot of ways,
it'll bring the team together.

244
00:14:47,261 --> 00:14:50,055
<i>I was under siege when the book came out.
Everyone turned on me,</i>

245
00:14:50,139 --> 00:14:52,266
<i>to the point where
I was getting a lot of threats</i>

246
00:14:52,349 --> 00:14:55,686
<i>and the newspaper had me stay home
for a week, told me not to come.</i>

247
00:14:58,147 --> 00:15:01,025
The Jordan Rules <i>took a big toll on him
off the court.</i>

248
00:15:02,443 --> 00:15:06,280
<i>But on the court, he was still
the most dominant figure in the game</i>

249
00:15:06,363 --> 00:15:07,865
<i>on the most dominant team.</i>

250
00:15:16,373 --> 00:15:18,667
<i>And Horace with the slam!</i>

251
00:15:18,751 --> 00:15:20,794
<i>Jordan intercepts.
What a play!</i>

252
00:15:20,878 --> 00:15:22,212
<i>They're tearing them apart.</i>

253
00:15:22,296 --> 00:15:24,924
<i>Fourteen.
Jordan past Petrovic.</i>

254
00:15:33,682 --> 00:15:36,518
<i>Michael blocked him...
...denied by Horace...</i>

255
00:15:36,602 --> 00:15:39,730
<i>...three on two. To Jordan. And a foul...</i>

256
00:15:39,813 --> 00:15:41,607
<i>Oh, he scored! Yes!</i>

257
00:15:46,195 --> 00:15:49,156
<i>Michael in control, feeds Horace Grant.</i>

258
00:15:49,823 --> 00:15:51,283
<i>Michael on the line.</i>

259
00:15:57,957 --> 00:16:02,336
<i>No fouling here.
From mid-court, a 50-footer to go...</i>

260
00:16:02,419 --> 00:16:03,587
<i>Michael Jordan!</i>

261
00:16:06,382 --> 00:16:08,258
A lot of the people in...

262
00:16:09,134 --> 00:16:12,888
that era that you would consider
Michael's peers had won two in a row.

263
00:16:13,472 --> 00:16:16,892
Isiah won two straight.
Magic had won two straight.

264
00:16:16,976 --> 00:16:19,395
But none of them won three in a row.

265
00:16:19,478 --> 00:16:22,606
A third championship was the separator.

266
00:16:22,690 --> 00:16:24,733
You win three, you're on Mount Rushmore.

267
00:16:25,609 --> 00:16:28,737
So, for that team, it was all about
winning a third straight.

268
00:16:29,321 --> 00:16:31,115
Who was their biggest obstacle?

269
00:16:31,657 --> 00:16:35,786
Without question,
it was this incredibly... tough,

270
00:16:36,412 --> 00:16:39,748
motivated and well-coached Knicks team.

271
00:16:42,376 --> 00:16:45,754
In the early '90s, the Knicks replaced
the Bad Boy Pistons

272
00:16:45,838 --> 00:16:48,132
as the team that Chicagoans
hated the most.

273
00:16:48,215 --> 00:16:51,468
It was very intense 'cause I know
how bad they wanted to beat us.

274
00:16:53,554 --> 00:16:55,472
<i>Both clubs going at each other.</i>

275
00:16:55,556 --> 00:16:58,684
<i>Michael Jordan and Xavier McDaniel
having words.</i>

276
00:16:58,767 --> 00:17:03,313
<i>Double technicals were called
on McDaniel and Jordan.</i>

277
00:17:04,732 --> 00:17:08,902
They were on the come up.
They were trying to be...

278
00:17:09,737 --> 00:17:14,533
the next Chicago Bulls
as we were to the Detroit Pistons.

279
00:17:15,909 --> 00:17:18,620
Mentally,
they were a hard-working team,

280
00:17:18,704 --> 00:17:23,751
but I firmly believe that...
when we were playing at our best

281
00:17:23,834 --> 00:17:26,253
and they're playing at their best,
we're a better team.

282
00:17:27,337 --> 00:17:30,883
Patrick Ewing was the biggest focus
for us, offensively.

283
00:17:31,717 --> 00:17:33,052
We hated each other.

284
00:17:34,553 --> 00:17:36,055
It was extremely physical.

285
00:17:38,015 --> 00:17:41,060
It wasn't really a foul
till you drew blood.

286
00:17:42,186 --> 00:17:43,854
When I was coaching the Knicks,

287
00:17:43,937 --> 00:17:46,440
I told the team,
"You can't let him dunk on you!"

288
00:17:48,150 --> 00:17:49,151
Hello!

289
00:17:52,488 --> 00:17:53,989
You gotta knock him down.

290
00:17:54,073 --> 00:17:57,493
If we don't meet him at the rim,
he's gonna embarrass you.

291
00:17:57,576 --> 00:18:00,996
<i>...ball that he followed up.
Jordan with the recovery. Jordan!</i>

292
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,544
Only way we can beat this guy,

293
00:18:07,628 --> 00:18:08,796
we had to hit him,

294
00:18:08,879 --> 00:18:11,298
let him know that
you just can't fly to the rim.

295
00:18:17,179 --> 00:18:19,139
The battle lines
were drawn between them.

296
00:18:19,515 --> 00:18:24,269
And then, 1993 playoffs, they're playing
the Knicks in the Conference Finals.

297
00:18:27,064 --> 00:18:28,984
<i>It has come down to this: game one</i>

298
00:18:29,066 --> 00:18:33,737
<i>of the eagerly anticipated best-of-seven
Eastern Conference Final.</i>

299
00:18:33,821 --> 00:18:35,864
<i>Patrick Ewing and his New York Knicks</i>

300
00:18:35,948 --> 00:18:38,742
<i>facing Michael Jordan
and the Chicago Bulls.</i>

301
00:18:39,868 --> 00:18:43,705
We got tested in that playoffs
by the Knicks.

302
00:18:45,916 --> 00:18:50,337
The Knicks had that same defense that
we'd just had to overcome versus Detroit.

303
00:18:50,921 --> 00:18:52,256
They were gonna be physical,

304
00:18:52,339 --> 00:18:54,883
they were gonna come up
body-to-body all the time.

305
00:18:54,967 --> 00:18:57,427
<i>Things beginning to get a bit rough.</i>

306
00:18:57,511 --> 00:18:58,929
That was a tremendous battle.

307
00:19:07,771 --> 00:19:10,983
<i>The basket counts and the foul!</i>

308
00:19:14,194 --> 00:19:18,323
<i>So the Knicks defeat the Bulls in game one
of this best-of-seven.</i>

309
00:19:20,033 --> 00:19:22,452
<i>Jordan knows that
all eyes are on him tonight</i>

310
00:19:22,536 --> 00:19:26,206
<i>as the Bulls go for the needed split in
New York in the Eastern Conference Finals.</i>

311
00:19:26,290 --> 00:19:28,792
<i>After shooting 3-for-13
in the second half Sunday,</i>

312
00:19:28,876 --> 00:19:30,878
<i>Jordan needs to light it up in game two.</i>

313
00:19:33,255 --> 00:19:34,815
<i>And Jordan... Just ran...</i>

314
00:19:34,840 --> 00:19:36,425
<i>He is walloped by Anthony!</i>

315
00:19:36,508 --> 00:19:38,468
<i>Now the Bulls are very upset.</i>

316
00:19:39,052 --> 00:19:40,804
In the second game
in the series,

317
00:19:40,888 --> 00:19:43,765
they were stepping things up,
really physical.

318
00:19:44,516 --> 00:19:45,893
<i>Ewing! And...</i>

319
00:19:46,852 --> 00:19:48,812
<i>Look out! Cartwright submarines.</i>

320
00:19:48,896 --> 00:19:50,772
<i>Starks! Yes!</i>

321
00:19:52,191 --> 00:19:57,196
<i>What a move by Starks,
who was able to sky to the basket!</i>

322
00:20:02,367 --> 00:20:05,162
<i>In sports, the Chicago Bulls
are down two games to none</i>

323
00:20:05,245 --> 00:20:07,331
<i>in their playoff series
with the New York Knicks.</i>

324
00:20:07,414 --> 00:20:11,919
<i>Some are suggesting that superstar
Michael Jordan may have dropped the ball.</i>

325
00:20:12,002 --> 00:20:14,546
<i>In the last quarter against
the Knicks Tuesday night,</i>

326
00:20:14,630 --> 00:20:16,381
<i>Michael Jordan looked tired.</i>

327
00:20:16,465 --> 00:20:20,344
<i>Was he worn down by the Knicks' defense
in a grueling physical game</i>

328
00:20:20,427 --> 00:20:21,762
<i>or was he worn down</i>

329
00:20:21,845 --> 00:20:25,891
<i>by a visit to this Atlantic City hotel
on the eve of the game?</i>

330
00:20:25,974 --> 00:20:27,935
<i>The </i>New York Times<i> said today</i>

331
00:20:28,018 --> 00:20:32,105
<i>Jordan was seen in the hotel's casino
as late as 2:30 in the morning.</i>

332
00:20:32,731 --> 00:20:34,816
My father said,
"Let's get away from New York City.

333
00:20:35,359 --> 00:20:37,361
Let's you and I go to Atlantic City."

334
00:20:37,444 --> 00:20:41,823
We got a limo, we went and gambled
for a couple of hours. We came back.

335
00:20:42,783 --> 00:20:46,828
Everybody went totally ballistic.
"Hey, he was in a casino last night."

336
00:20:47,412 --> 00:20:50,040
I wasn't late.
We got home by 12:30, one o'clock.

337
00:20:50,123 --> 00:20:53,293
The reason I was there was more or less
to get away from New York,

338
00:20:53,377 --> 00:20:57,297
hear about all the losing,
you know, the game situation.

339
00:20:57,381 --> 00:20:59,341
I went out to get my mind away
from basketball.

340
00:20:59,424 --> 00:21:00,676
I couldn't go play golf,

341
00:21:00,759 --> 00:21:03,011
so I rode up there
with my family and friends.

342
00:21:03,095 --> 00:21:05,555
<i>Jordan's hours
triggered harsh headlines</i>

343
00:21:05,639 --> 00:21:07,641
<i>and dominated the sports talk shows.</i>

344
00:21:07,724 --> 00:21:10,435
What it shows me is a lack of commitment

345
00:21:10,519 --> 00:21:13,438
to what is the goal right now,
and that is a third championship.

346
00:21:13,522 --> 00:21:18,485
<i>Jordan had violated no team rules,
no league rules, no state laws.</i>

347
00:21:18,568 --> 00:21:22,072
<i>All he violated
were people's expectations.</i>

348
00:21:23,323 --> 00:21:26,451
I addressed the
Atlantic City thing, and he was like,

349
00:21:26,994 --> 00:21:30,247
"Going down to Atlantic City in the
afternoon and getting back at midnight?

350
00:21:30,330 --> 00:21:32,666
That's not gonna affect my basketball.

351
00:21:32,749 --> 00:21:34,835
It's gonna take my mind away

352
00:21:35,419 --> 00:21:38,046
from this pressure
we have building up in the playoffs."

353
00:21:38,797 --> 00:21:41,341
Why was the trip
to Atlantic City such a big deal?

354
00:21:41,425 --> 00:21:43,385
Okay, the backstory is this.

355
00:21:43,468 --> 00:21:46,638
So, the Bulls win in '91.
They win the championship.

356
00:21:47,222 --> 00:21:49,766
You go to the White House
when you win the championship.

357
00:21:49,850 --> 00:21:51,101
Ready. Get set...

358
00:21:51,184 --> 00:21:53,228
Except Jordan didn't show.

359
00:21:54,187 --> 00:21:56,815
He said, "Time with family. I gotta be..."

360
00:21:56,898 --> 00:21:58,942
No, he was out gambling with Slim Bouler.

361
00:22:03,155 --> 00:22:05,741
Slim Bouler was a golf hustler

362
00:22:05,824 --> 00:22:09,619
and back in December of 1991,

363
00:22:10,203 --> 00:22:13,999
he was brought up on drug
and money laundering charges.

364
00:22:14,624 --> 00:22:19,796
And federal agents found a check
made out from Michael Jordan

365
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:23,091
to Slim Bouler for $57,000.

366
00:22:23,175 --> 00:22:25,969
Jordan initially said,
"That was just a loan I made him."

367
00:22:26,845 --> 00:22:32,517
But Michael was a witness in this case
involving Slim Bouler,

368
00:22:32,601 --> 00:22:36,646
and Michael admitted
that he was repaying a gambling debt.

369
00:22:36,730 --> 00:22:39,483
<i>"What was the money for?"
asked Bouler's attorney.</i>

370
00:22:39,566 --> 00:22:43,445
<i>Answer: "It was what I lost gambling.
It was never a loan.</i>

371
00:22:43,528 --> 00:22:47,240
<i>I said it was a loan strictly to save
the embarrassment and pain."</i>

372
00:22:47,866 --> 00:22:51,286
So, when Michael spends
all night gambling in Atlantic City,

373
00:22:51,370 --> 00:22:55,874
after they lost game one,
it became a very public issue

374
00:22:55,957 --> 00:23:01,046
in terms of, "Is this signs of
some kind of a problem with him?"

375
00:23:01,129 --> 00:23:04,716
And then you add to that
the Esquinas book,

376
00:23:05,425 --> 00:23:09,513
which came out in the midst
of that Atlantic City fiasco.

377
00:23:09,596 --> 00:23:13,392
In a book titled
<i>Michael and Me: Our Gambling Addiction,</i>

378
00:23:13,475 --> 00:23:15,977
Richard Esquinas,
a onetime general manager

379
00:23:16,061 --> 00:23:17,646
of the San Diego Sports Arena,

380
00:23:17,729 --> 00:23:22,692
makes the claim that Michael Jordan
owed him more than $1.2 million,

381
00:23:22,776 --> 00:23:25,278
a result of gambling
on their golf matches.

382
00:23:25,737 --> 00:23:28,949
Yeah, Richard Esquinas...
We met from a third party.

383
00:23:29,032 --> 00:23:32,119
I'm actually playing golf with people
all the time now.

384
00:23:32,202 --> 00:23:33,745
If they wanna gamble, we gamble.

385
00:23:33,829 --> 00:23:35,622
The character of those individuals,

386
00:23:35,705 --> 00:23:39,501
I found out later what kind of people
I was playing with.

387
00:23:39,584 --> 00:23:41,628
I learned that lesson.

388
00:23:41,711 --> 00:23:44,756
But the act of gambling,
I didn't do anything wrong.

389
00:23:44,840 --> 00:23:50,345
And it right away went right to the most
deepest, darkest kind of side of it.

390
00:23:50,429 --> 00:23:51,888
Is he throwing games?

391
00:23:52,472 --> 00:23:54,224
Has it gone beyond golf?

392
00:23:54,307 --> 00:23:56,017
Never has. Never has.

393
00:23:56,101 --> 00:23:58,854
Michael and I were competitive
and gambling on the golf course.

394
00:23:58,937 --> 00:24:00,188
We play cards.

395
00:24:00,272 --> 00:24:04,234
I was in many of the card games,
but never anything else.

396
00:24:04,317 --> 00:24:08,321
I never bet on games, I only bet
on myself and that was golf.

397
00:24:08,989 --> 00:24:11,783
Do I like to play blackjack?
Yeah, I like playing blackjack.

398
00:24:11,867 --> 00:24:13,034
There's no laws with that.

399
00:24:13,118 --> 00:24:16,288
And the league did call me
and they asked questions about it,

400
00:24:16,371 --> 00:24:18,415
and I told them
exactly what was happening.

401
00:24:19,499 --> 00:24:24,254
Michael was betting
on his golf game.

402
00:24:24,337 --> 00:24:28,758
Larger numbers than you or I might bet
if we played golf together.

403
00:24:28,842 --> 00:24:32,596
But, you know,
given Michael's earnings and the like,

404
00:24:32,679 --> 00:24:37,767
we just never... It never reached
epic crisis levels in my view.

405
00:24:42,522 --> 00:24:44,441
I understand that people

406
00:24:44,524 --> 00:24:46,776
would see and hear about
amounts of money like that

407
00:24:46,860 --> 00:24:48,528
and go, "Wow! That's a lot of money."

408
00:24:48,612 --> 00:24:51,364
What I used to always say
to people is that,

409
00:24:51,448 --> 00:24:55,744
for Michael Jordan,
$10,000 is like you gambling $10.

410
00:24:55,827 --> 00:24:59,289
He's got it. He's good for it.
You don't have to worry about it.

411
00:24:59,372 --> 00:25:00,916
The thought has occurred

412
00:25:00,999 --> 00:25:03,919
that you aren't really gambling
with money,

413
00:25:04,002 --> 00:25:06,421
you're gambling with your reputation.

414
00:25:07,005 --> 00:25:08,924
Gambling with your good name.

415
00:25:09,633 --> 00:25:13,720
What would they consider my good name?
The purest of all pure?

416
00:25:14,513 --> 00:25:16,806
The person that doesn't make mistakes?

417
00:25:16,890 --> 00:25:20,852
It wasn't all part of this
carefully cultivated image

418
00:25:20,936 --> 00:25:24,523
that he had had of being
the best basketball player in the world

419
00:25:24,606 --> 00:25:26,650
that everyone wanted to be like.

420
00:25:26,733 --> 00:25:29,361
Do you think you have
a gambling problem at all?

421
00:25:29,444 --> 00:25:32,113
No. Because I can stop gambling.

422
00:25:32,197 --> 00:25:33,949
I have a competition problem.

423
00:25:35,116 --> 00:25:36,409
A competitive problem.

424
00:25:36,993 --> 00:25:41,039
It didn't affect his endorsements.
It didn't affect him monetarily.

425
00:25:41,122 --> 00:25:43,083
It didn't really affect his popularity.

426
00:25:43,959 --> 00:25:46,419
But the damage was to his reputation.

427
00:25:47,546 --> 00:25:52,259
And the price to pay
was how tedious this all became

428
00:25:52,342 --> 00:25:56,012
for Michael to have to
answer these questions.

429
00:26:00,475 --> 00:26:03,228
Were you playing
$1,000-a-hole golf down there?

430
00:26:03,311 --> 00:26:05,981
- Is that what was going on?
- Is this an addiction?

431
00:26:06,064 --> 00:26:08,400
When you're answering these questions
over and over again,

432
00:26:08,483 --> 00:26:12,153
and feeling you have to defend yourself,
it's exhausting.

433
00:26:12,737 --> 00:26:14,823
Get 'em off the floor. It's one o'clock.

434
00:26:14,906 --> 00:26:16,116
Let's start it up.

435
00:26:16,700 --> 00:26:22,247
He was really starting
to grate against the media onslaught.

436
00:26:22,330 --> 00:26:25,792
Michael becomes irate
and refuses to talk to the media.

437
00:26:26,793 --> 00:26:28,962
The curtain of silence
started to come down.

438
00:26:30,005 --> 00:26:31,506
He wanted no part of it.

439
00:26:31,590 --> 00:26:34,593
Let someone like his dad
have to answer these questions for him.

440
00:26:35,093 --> 00:26:37,721
I stopped talking.
My father said, "Let me handle this."

441
00:26:37,804 --> 00:26:40,515
I said, "Dad, you don't have to."
He said, "Nah." He wanted to.

442
00:26:40,599 --> 00:26:44,019
He has given the best of him.

443
00:26:44,102 --> 00:26:48,565
He has sacrificed
to try to satisfy everybody.

444
00:26:49,107 --> 00:26:52,694
And after doing all of that,
people still find a way of knocking him.

445
00:26:52,777 --> 00:26:55,280
And he's saying,
"Damn, how much is enough?"

446
00:26:58,783 --> 00:27:02,120
Around that time,
I remember Magic Johnson saying,

447
00:27:02,704 --> 00:27:05,290
"You guys are gonna drive him
out of this game

448
00:27:05,373 --> 00:27:07,834
if you keep this up,
'cause he's tired of it.

449
00:27:07,917 --> 00:27:09,878
He's tired of you guys picking on him."

450
00:27:15,216 --> 00:27:17,302
People build you up
to tear you down.

451
00:27:18,178 --> 00:27:19,929
It happens in sports all the time.

452
00:27:20,013 --> 00:27:22,974
If a team wins too much,
you want 'em to lose.

453
00:27:26,353 --> 00:27:30,982
The public has an appetite for
these kind of rise-and-fall narratives.

454
00:27:34,986 --> 00:27:37,447
Let's go, baby! Let's go!

455
00:27:38,031 --> 00:27:40,950
I think he was disgusted
with what happened,

456
00:27:41,034 --> 00:27:43,286
and Michael had to respond.

457
00:27:45,664 --> 00:27:46,998
And respond he did.

458
00:27:49,668 --> 00:27:51,586
<i>Here's Jordan for the fadeaway.</i>

459
00:27:54,047 --> 00:27:55,840
<i>Jordan off the hesitation dribble!</i>

